To define the scope of undertakings to which the Business Expenditure on Research and Development Survey Order 2022 applies, we need to consider the information provided in the passages.

Regulation 2 of the Order defines the scope of undertakings as follows:

* Information regarding the nature of its business activity insofar as it relates to R&D in 2021 (Regulation 1(i));
* Expenditure on in-house R&D activity in 2021 (Regulation 1(h));
* Estimated expenditure on in-house R&D activity in 2022 (Regulation 1(e));
* Sources of funds for in-house R&D activity performed in 2021 and the amount in euro from each source concerned (Regulation 1(f));
* Categories of in-house R&D activity performed in 2021 and the expenditure on each category concerned (Regulation 1(f));
* The number of persons involved in in-house R&D activity in 2021 including, in relation to each such person, his or her role, qualifications and gender and the amount of time spent by him or her on that activity (Regulation 1(i));
* R&D activity at local unit level in 2021 (Regulation 1(j));
* Expenditure on R&D activity performed on behalf of the undertaking by other persons in 2021 (Regulation 1(h));
* By reference to the qualifications of the persons concerned, whether the undertaking is likely, in the period commencing on 1 January 2022 and ending on 31 December 2027, to increase the number of persons involved in in-house R&D activity (Regulation 1(i));
* Engagement in 2021 by the undertaking with other persons in joint R&D projects (Regulation 1(j)).

Additionally, the Order requires information regarding the time taken by the undertaking concerned to complete the form, questionnaire or other record prepared by the Director General for the collection of information referred to in paragraph 1 (Regulation 2).

Therefore, the scope of undertakings to which the Business Expenditure on Research and Development Survey Order 2022 applies includes:

* Undertakings that have in-house R&D activity in 2021 and 2022;
* Undertakings that have R&D activity at local unit level in 2021;
* Undertakings that engage in joint R&D projects in 2021;
* Undertakings that are likely to increase the number of persons involved in in-house R&D activity in the period commencing on 1 January 2022 and ending on 31 December 2027.

It is worth noting that the Order also requires information regarding the nature of the business activity insofar as it relates to R&D in 2021, 2023, and 2019, and the expenditure on in-house R&D activity in 2023 and 2019. However, these requirements are not directly related to the scope of undertakings to which the Order applies.

